<section class="card">
  <h2>Why First Frost Dates Matter</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Sets harvest deadlines for warm-season crops.</li>
    <li>Defines “is it too late?” decisions for fall planting.</li>
    <li>Helps prioritize protection when cold nights arrive early.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Warm-season crops like tomatoes, peppers, beans, cucumbers, and zucchini usually stop after a hard freeze — and can be damaged even by brief freezing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Count Backward From First Frost</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Find your average first frost date.</li>
    <li>Count backward using the crop’s days to maturity.</li>
    <li>Add a buffer (often 7–10 days) because fall growth slows.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Example:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>First frost: October 1</li>
    <li>Crop maturity: 60 days</li>
    <li>Target planting: late July (or earlier with buffer)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Happens at 32°F (0°C)?</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Light frost:</strong> surface frost forms; leaves can be damaged.</li>
    <li><strong>Hard freeze:</strong> prolonged freezing; most warm-season crops die.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Even without visible frost, repeated nights near freezing can slow growth and reduce ripening.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What to Do If Frost Is Forecast Early</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Harvest ripe produce immediately.</li>
    <li>Cover plants for a light frost if it changes the outcome.</li>
    <li>Pick near-mature fruit before a hard freeze.</li>
    <li>Prioritize your most frost-sensitive crops first.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In cold northern U.S. climates and comparable Canadian regions, early fall frost is common enough to plan for every year.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Is the first frost date exact?</summary>
    <p>No. It’s an average based on historical data.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can frost occur before the average date?</summary>
    <p>Yes. Freezing can arrive earlier in some years, which is why buffers help in short seasons.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is first frost the same as a hard freeze?</summary>
    <p>No. First frost can be light; a hard freeze involves longer time below 32°F / 0°C.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Does this apply in Canada?</summary>
    <p>Yes. Frost-based timing applies across cold regions in both the U.S. and Canada.</p>
  </details>
</section>

